      <lido:objectDescriptionWrap>
        <lido:objectDescriptionSet>
          <lido:descriptiveNoteValue>The story of Salmacis and Hermaphroditus comes from Ovid's Metamorphoses. The nymph Salmacis fell in love Hermaphroditus, the son of Hermes and Aphrodite. Hermaphroditus rejected her, but Salmacis outwitted him in the water. Still, he wanted to know nothing about her, and then Salmacis begged the gods to unite her with him forever. Both fused into a hermaphrodite, an androgynous being with both male and female kenmerken.François Joseph Navez them just painted for the metamorphosis. Coy gesture Hermaphroditus and the passionate embrace of the lovelorn nymph form an ingenious and elegant ballet in an almost abstracted lines. Mythological scenes were rather an exception in the work of Navez. His stay in Rome inspired him throughout his career rather to religious subjects and picturesque Italian scenes. With his classic portraits, he was very successful.</lido:descriptiveNoteValue>
        </lido:objectDescriptionSet>
